/* Scrum PSM I / CSM-style practice pool — 200 questions.
   Open Assessment draws a random, shuffled set of 20 each attempt. */
window.SCRUM_QA = [
{q:"What is the primary purpose of Scrum?",a:["To eliminate all project risks before development starts","To enforce strict adherence to detailed plans","To help people, teams, and organizations generate value through adaptive solutions for complex problems","To ensure every project is completed on schedule"],c:2,e:"Scrum is a lightweight framework for generating value with complex problems through iterative, empirical processes. It emphasizes adaptiveness and learning rather than predictive risk elimination or schedule certainty."},
{q:"Which statement best describes empiricism in Scrum?",a:["Team members should follow written instructions strictly.","Decisions are based on observation, experience, and experimentation.","All requirements are fixed upfront.","The Product Owner makes all project decisions based on intuition."],c:1,e:"Scrum is founded on empiricism: knowledge comes from experience and making decisions on what is observed. Transparency and inspection enable this empirical decision-making; adaptation follows when new data emerges."},
{q:"Which of the following is not one of Scrum's five values?",a:["Commitment","Courage","Respect","Innovation"],c:3,e:"The Scrum values are Commitment, Courage, Focus, Openness, and Respect. While innovation is encouraged in Agile contexts, it is not listed as a Scrum value in the Scrum Guide."},
{q:"Which Scrum pillar ensures work and progress are visible to everyone?",a:["Inspection","Adaptation","Transparency","Optimization"],c:2,e:"Transparency is a Scrum pillar that makes the emergent work and progress visible to all participants. Without transparency, inspection of artifacts is misleading."},
{q:"During a Sprint, developers discover new work that could enhance the product. What is the best action for the Developers to take first?",a:["Add the work to the Sprint Backlog and start it immediately.","Cancel the Sprint and start planning anew.","Ignore it until Sprint Review.","Discuss the potential work with the Product Owner and adapt the Sprint Backlog if it fits the Sprint Goal."],c:3,e:"The Sprint Backlog is adaptive; the Developers may collaborate with the Product Owner if new work is discovered, to see if it aligns with the Sprint Goal. They should not cancel the Sprint unless the Sprint Goal becomes obsolete."},
{q:"Who is accountable for maximizing the value of the product in Scrum?",a:["The Scrum Master","The Product Owner","The Developers","The Project Manager"],c:1,e:"The Product Owner is accountable for product value through effective Product Backlog management. Scrum has no Project Manager role; only the Product Owner decides on value-driven ordering and backlog content."},
{q:"Which Scrum role is accountable for helping teams and the organization understand and enact Scrum?",a:["Product Owner","Scrum Master","Team Lead","Project Manager"],c:1,e:"The Scrum Master is responsible for promoting and supporting Scrum as defined by the Scrum Guide, helping everyone understand Scrum theory, practices, rules, and values. They serve as a servant-leader coach."},
{q:"What is the maximum duration of a Sprint in Scrum?",a:["Two weeks","One month","Three months","It depends on team preference"],c:1,e:"A Sprint is a fixed time-box of one month or less. Shorter Sprints are common, but they may not be longer than one calendar month, to ensure frequent inspection and adaptation."},
{q:"Who owns the Sprint Backlog during a Sprint?",a:["The Product Owner","The Scrum Master","The Developers (Scrum Team)","Stakeholders"],c:2,e:"The Sprint Backlog is owned and managed by the Developers. It includes the Sprint Goal, selected Product Backlog Items, and the plan. Only the Developers decide how to implement the work."},
{q:"What is the primary purpose of the Daily Scrum?",a:["To report progress to management","To inspect progress toward the Sprint Goal and adapt the Sprint Backlog","To create the Sprint Backlog","To demo completed work"],c:1,e:"The Daily Scrum is a 15-minute time-boxed event for Developers to inspect progress toward the Sprint Goal and adjust their plan for the next 24 hours. It is not a reporting session for management."},
{q:"Who has the authority to cancel a Sprint?",a:["The Product Owner","The Scrum Master","The Developers","The Stakeholders"],c:0,e:"Only the Product Owner can cancel a Sprint, and only if the Sprint Goal becomes obsolete. Neither Developers nor Scrum Master alone have this authority."},
{q:"Which artifact provides transparency into what the Scrum Team plans to accomplish during the Sprint?",a:["Product Backlog","Sprint Backlog","Release Plan","Burn-down Chart"],c:1,e:"The Sprint Backlog contains the Sprint Goal, the selected Product Backlog Items, and the plan for delivering them. It is a live artifact that shows what the Developers are working on in the current Sprint."},
{q:"What is the Product Goal in Scrum?",a:["A fixed release date for the product.","The commitment used to measure team performance.","A long-term objective for the Scrum Team, describing a future state of the product.","A list of tasks for the next Sprint."],c:2,e:"The Product Goal is the long-term objective for the Scrum Team, providing focus toward a valuable future state of the product. It resides in the Product Backlog as a commitment."},
{q:"Which Scrum event focuses on inspecting the Increment and adapting the Product Backlog with stakeholders?",a:["Sprint Planning","Sprint Review","Sprint Retrospective","Daily Scrum"],c:1,e:"The Sprint Review occurs at the end of the Sprint to inspect the Increment and collaborate on next steps. Stakeholders and the Scrum Team review what was Done and discuss possible future backlog items."},
{q:"What is the main purpose of the Sprint Retrospective?",a:["To estimate the Product Backlog.","To review stakeholder requirements.","To inspect and adapt the team's process and improve how the team works.","To demonstrate the Increment to the Product Owner."],c:2,e:"The Sprint Retrospective is an event for the Scrum Team to inspect itself and identify ways to become more effective. It focuses on the team's processes and interactions, generating actionable improvements."},
{q:"Which statement about the Definition of Done (DoD) is true?",a:["It is optional and used only in large organizations.","It defines the quality measures required for an Increment to be releasable.","It changes daily at the Daily Scrum.","Only the Scrum Master can create it."],c:1,e:"The Definition of Done is a formal description of the state of the Increment when it meets required quality measures. It is mandatory and usually agreed by the Developers."},
{q:"What happens to a Product Backlog Item that does not meet the Definition of Done by the end of a Sprint?",a:["It is automatically released with a note of exceptions.","It is included in the Sprint Increment anyway.","It cannot be considered part of the Increment; it returns to the Product Backlog.","The Sprint is cancelled."],c:2,e:"If a PBI does not meet the Definition of Done, it is incomplete and cannot be included in the Increment. Instead, it goes back to the Product Backlog for future consideration."},
{q:"Which Agile Manifesto value emphasizes collaboration with customers over contractual details?",a:["Working software over comprehensive documentation","Customer collaboration over contract negotiation","Individuals and interactions over processes and tools","Responding to change over following a plan"],c:1,e:"The Agile Manifesto value 'Customer collaboration over contract negotiation' highlights prioritizing direct collaboration and customer feedback rather than relying solely on formal contracts."},
{q:"Why should Scrum Teams be cross-functional?",a:["To reduce external dependencies by having all necessary skills on the team.","To increase the number of team members.","To allow the Scrum Master to assign tasks more easily.","To eliminate the need for a Product Owner."],c:0,e:"Cross-functional teams have all the skills needed to deliver value without external dependencies. This reduces handoffs and delays, enabling the team to self-manage the work."},
{q:"During a Sprint, a stakeholder asks the Developers to add a high-priority item not in the Sprint Backlog. What should they do first?",a:["Accept the request and adjust the Sprint Backlog immediately.","Ask the Scrum Master to decline the request.","Discuss with the Product Owner to assess impact on the Sprint Goal.","Tell the stakeholder to wait until next Sprint without discussion."],c:2,e:"Any mid-Sprint change should be evaluated by the Developers and Product Owner against the Sprint Goal. The Product Owner may decide to adjust scope, but Developers should not unilaterally accept or reject requests without this discussion."},
{q:"Which Scrum role facilitates Scrum events as needed?",a:["Product Owner","Scrum Master","Developers","Project Manager"],c:1,e:"The Scrum Master ensures that Scrum events take place and are productive, facilitating them when needed. They help the team and organization follow Scrum but do not manage the team's work directly."},
{q:"What is the primary purpose of Product Backlog Refinement?",a:["To create release schedules.","To add detail, estimates, and order to Product Backlog items so they are ready for future Sprints.","To finalize the Definition of Done.","To hold a meeting for stakeholder sign-off."],c:1,e:"Product Backlog Refinement is the ongoing act of breaking down and clarifying Product Backlog items, adding details like description, size, and order. It prepares PBIs for future Sprints."},
{q:"Which metric represents the amount of work completed by a Scrum Team in past Sprints and is used for planning?",a:["Cycle Time","Velocity","Burn-up Rate","Throughput"],c:1,e:"Velocity is the sum of the work completed in past Sprints. Teams often use it for forecasting future Sprint capacity, but it is not a target and should not be used to measure productivity per se."},
{q:"During Sprint Planning, who decides how the selected Product Backlog items will be accomplished?",a:["The Product Owner","The Scrum Master","The Developers","The Stakeholders"],c:2,e:"The Developers are responsible for creating the plan to deliver the selected PBIs. They determine the how because they have the technical expertise. The Product Owner does not direct how work is done."},
{q:"Which statement best reflects Agile thinking?",a:["Change should be minimized after requirements are fixed.","Teams should welcome changing requirements that improve customer value.","Processes and tools are more important than individuals and interactions.","Contracts should dictate all project details."],c:1,e:"An Agile Manifesto principle is to welcome changing requirements, even late in development, as change can enhance customer value. Agile values individuals over strict processes and working solutions over rigid contracts."},
{q:"Who is responsible for ensuring that the Scrum Team understands the product domain as much as possible?",a:["The Scrum Master","The Developers","The Product Owner","The Stakeholders"],c:2,e:"While the Scrum Master helps ensure goals, scope, and the product domain are understood, the Product Owner is primarily accountable for maximizing product value and ensuring shared understanding of the product."},
{q:"In Scrum, the Sprint Review should be conducted:",a:["Only if stakeholders are available.","At the same time and place each day.","Before the Sprint Retrospective.","After the Sprint Planning."],c:2,e:"The Sprint Review occurs near the end of the Sprint, after the Increment is prepared, and typically before the Sprint Retrospective which closes the Sprint. It is not daily; that refers to the Daily Scrum."},
{q:"What is the key accountability of the Developers in a Scrum Team?",a:["Ordering the Product Backlog","Managing the Scrum events","Delivering a Done, usable, and potentially releasable Increment each Sprint","Ensuring the Definition of Done is met by others"],c:2,e:"Developers are accountable for creating the Increment that meets the Definition of Done. They manage the Sprint Backlog and ensure the Increment is usable. They do not order the Product Backlog or decide the Scrum process."},
{q:"Which statement about time-boxes in Scrum is true?",a:["Time-boxes are minimum durations for events.","Sprint time-box is flexible and can be extended if needed.","A Daily Scrum is time-boxed to 15 minutes maximum.","Time-boxes apply only to the Sprint Planning."],c:2,e:"Scrum events are time-boxed, meaning they have a fixed maximum duration. The Daily Scrum is time-boxed to 15 minutes and a Sprint to one month at most. Time-boxes are a maximum, not a minimum."},
{q:"What does it mean for a Scrum Team to be self-managing?",a:["Team members get to pick their own salaries.","The team collectively chooses how to accomplish the work, without direction from outsiders.","The Scrum Master assigns tasks to each Developer.","The Product Owner delegates sprint tasks to the team."],c:1,e:"Self-managing means the team has the autonomy to decide who does what, how work gets done, and how to organize themselves to achieve the Sprint Goal. They do not wait for external managers to assign tasks."},
{q:"How are impediments handled in Scrum?",a:["The Scrum Master removes impediments for the team.","Developers should ignore impediments during the Sprint.","The Product Owner is responsible for removing impediments.","Stakeholders must be consulted to remove impediments."],c:0,e:"The Scrum Master serves the Developers by removing impediments and working to improve team productivity. Developers should raise impediments early, and the Scrum Master helps address them."},
{q:"What is the Sprint Goal?",a:["A list of tasks for the Sprint.","The reason or objective for the Sprint, providing coherence to the work.","The Definition of Done for the Sprint.","The deadline for the Sprint."],c:1,e:"The Sprint Goal is the single objective for the Sprint. It provides context and focus for the work and is the commitment of the Sprint Backlog."},
{q:"During Sprint Planning, the Scrum Team identifies 'what' and 'how'. The 2020 Scrum Guide added emphasis on a third topic. What is it?",a:["'Who' will do the work.","'When' each task will be completed.","'Why' (the Sprint Goal).","'Where' the team will meet."],c:2,e:"Besides What (the work) and How (the plan), the 2020 Scrum Guide explicitly emphasizes Why — the Sprint Goal — in Sprint Planning, to give the Sprint purpose and direction."},
{q:"Which Scrum artifact is described as 'an emergent, ordered list of what is needed to improve the product'?",a:["Definition of Done","Product Backlog","Sprint Backlog","Increment"],c:1,e:"The Product Backlog is an emergent, ordered list of what is needed to improve the product. It is the single source of work for the Scrum Team."},
{q:"What is the purpose of the Definition of Done (DoD) in Scrum?",a:["To describe team roles and responsibilities.","To provide a shared understanding of when work is complete, ensuring transparency of quality.","To assign Story Points to backlog items.","To determine the Sprint Goal."],c:1,e:"The Definition of Done provides everyone a shared understanding of what Done means for work items. It ensures transparency and quality by clearly stating the criteria for an Increment to be releasable."},
{q:"In Scrum, who decides which Product Backlog items will be taken into a Sprint during Sprint Planning?",a:["The Product Owner alone, choosing by priority.","The Developers alone, based on their capacity.","The Developers, considering the Sprint Goal and capacity, with input from the Product Owner.","The Scrum Master assigns the items to the Developers."],c:2,e:"The whole Scrum Team collaborates in Sprint Planning. The Developers select PBIs they forecast to complete, guided by the Sprint Goal, while the Product Owner clarifies priorities. No one assigns tasks to them."},
{q:"Which statement about Sprint length is true in Scrum?",a:["Shorter Sprints are discouraged because they increase overhead.","The length of each Sprint should be the same throughout a development effort.","Sprints can vary in length based on team preference.","A Sprint can be canceled and restarted with the same time-box."],c:1,e:"Sprints are a consistent time-box throughout development. A team uses the same Sprint length repeatedly to establish a rhythm and predictability. Changing lengths frequently reduces predictability."},
{q:"What is Sprint execution primarily focused on?",a:["Adhering strictly to the initial plan without deviation.","Achieving the Sprint Goal by completing backlog items and adapting as needed.","Maximizing the number of story points completed.","Preparing the next Release Plan."],c:1,e:"During Sprint execution, the Developers work to achieve the Sprint Goal by completing backlog items. They inspect progress in Daily Scrums and adapt the plan or scope to meet the Goal."},
{q:"Which event in Scrum is primarily for inspecting and adapting team practices and is attended only by the Scrum Team (no external stakeholders)?",a:["Sprint Review","Sprint Retrospective","Sprint Planning","Daily Scrum"],c:1,e:"The Sprint Retrospective is solely for the Scrum Team to inspect and improve their processes. External stakeholders are not invited. The Sprint Review is the collaborative event with stakeholders."},
{q:"When is the Sprint Backlog updated?",a:["Only during Sprint Planning.","At the end of the Sprint.","Continuously throughout the Sprint as work is learned and the plan changes.","Never; it is fixed once the Sprint starts."],c:2,e:"The Sprint Backlog is a living artifact updated by the Developers throughout the Sprint as more is learned. It reflects current tasks and progress so the team can inspect and adapt in Daily Scrums."},
{q:"What ensures that the Increment delivered at the end of each Sprint is potentially releasable?",a:["The Scrum Master's inspection.","The stakeholders' approval.","Adherence to the Definition of Done for all Product Backlog Items.","Completing all tasks in the Sprint Backlog."],c:2,e:"An Increment is potentially releasable only when all its PBIs meet the Definition of Done. The DoD is the quality standard; if anything is incomplete, the Increment cannot be considered done or released."},
{q:"Who is accountable for clear communication of the Product Goal?",a:["The Scrum Master","The Product Owner","The Developers","The Project Sponsor"],c:1,e:"The Product Owner is accountable for effectively communicating the Product Goal to the Scrum Team. The Scrum Master may coach the PO on communication, but the ultimate accountability lies with the PO."},
{q:"Which statement about Scrum events is false?",a:["The Daily Scrum is time-boxed to 15 minutes.","The Sprint Retrospective is for inspecting the product increment with stakeholders.","Sprint Planning sets the Sprint Goal.","The Sprint Review may invite stakeholders for feedback."],c:1,e:"The false statement is B. The Sprint Retrospective is for inspecting the team's process, not the product increment, and it is for the Scrum Team only. The Sprint Review is the event with stakeholders."},
{q:"How does the Scrum framework relate to project management?",a:["Scrum completely replaces all project management in an organization.","Scrum provides a lightweight framework; project management can overlay it as needed.","Scrum requires a traditional project plan at the start.","Project management metrics are mandated in Scrum."],c:1,e:"Scrum is an agile framework, not a replacement for all organizational governance. Project management processes can exist alongside it. Scrum emphasizes empirical control rather than traditional plans or mandated metrics."},
{q:"In Scrum, a Release Plan is:",a:["Required before any product work begins.","A fixed schedule that must never change.","An optional forecast to help release decisions, but not mandated by Scrum.","The same as the Sprint Backlog."],c:2,e:"Scrum does not mandate a release plan. Teams often create release plans using empirical data (velocity) as a forecast that may adapt frequently. It is not defined in the Scrum Guide but is used for stakeholder communication."},
{q:"Why are all Scrum Teams on a product said to share the same Product Goal?",a:["Because they all work on exactly the same Sprint Backlog.","Because the Product Goal ensures coherence by aligning the Scrum Team(s) around a common long-term objective.","Because only one Scrum Team can exist per Product Goal.","Because the Product Owner cannot write multiple goals."],c:1,e:"Multiple Scrum Teams working on the same product share one Product Goal. This focuses all teams on delivering toward one unified long-term objective, preventing silos."},
{q:"What is the relationship between the Increment and the Product Goal?",a:["The Increment should move the product closer to the Product Goal each Sprint.","The Product Goal is always met by a single Increment.","The Increment and Product Goal are the same artifact.","The Product Goal is only for Sprint Planning, while the Increment is only for Sprint Review."],c:0,e:"Each Sprint's Increment should be a step toward the Product Goal. The Product Goal provides direction; it is long-term, so multiple Increments may be needed to reach it."},
{q:"What aspect of Scrum is empirical?",a:["Product Backlog prioritization","Sprint Planning estimation","The entire process of development (inspect & adapt)","Team building"],c:2,e:"Scrum is built on empiricism: the entire development process is iterative, with frequent inspections and adaptations. It is the empirical cycle of transparency, inspection, and adaptation that defines Scrum."},
{q:"The Sprint Backlog is updated during the Sprint. Which statement is true?",a:["Only the Scrum Master may update the Sprint Backlog.","The Sprint Backlog is a plan by and for the Developers, and they may update it as more is learned.","The Sprint Backlog remains fixed after Sprint Planning.","The Product Owner updates the Sprint Backlog when stakeholders request changes."],c:1,e:"The Sprint Backlog is owned by the Developers and updated throughout the Sprint as the team learns more. The Scrum Master or Product Owner does not manage its contents."},
{q:"What is one of the uses of Scrum as stated in Scrum Guide historical changes?",a:["Managing and developing products only.","Coordinating activities between multiple organization functions.","Managing complex adaptive problems beyond product development (e.g., operations, research).","Replacing all Agile methodologies."],c:2,e:"Scrum's use has expanded to many domains beyond software, including operations and marketing, to address complex adaptive problems. It complements other methods rather than replacing them."},
{q:"How should features and defects be handled in the Product Backlog?",a:["Only features belong in the Product Backlog; defects are handled outside Scrum.","Both new features and defects (technical work, chores) should be captured as Product Backlog items if they are needed for value.","Defects must always be fixed immediately during the Sprint, not planned.","Features go into Sprint Backlog, defects go into Product Backlog."],c:1,e:"The Product Backlog should include all types of work needed to achieve the Product Goal: features, defects, technical work, and knowledge acquisition. Both features and defects can be prioritized by value."},
{q:"During a Sprint, a Developer realizes a backlog item is too large and unclear. What should be done?",a:["Cancel the Sprint and re-plan.","Remove it and never address it.","Refine the item by splitting it into smaller ones or clarifying it during the Sprint, with the team's collaboration.","Delay it to the next year."],c:2,e:"If a PBI is too large or unclear, Developers should break it into smaller, clearer items to ensure transparency. Splitting and clarifying helps the team deliver value; it is not necessary to cancel the Sprint."},
{q:"Which of the following best describes the Developers' forecast for a Sprint?",a:["It's an immutable commitment to complete the Sprint Backlog.","It's a reliable prediction, because the future is certain.","It's an estimate of what can be done, acknowledging empirical uncertainty.","It's a guarantee given by the Scrum Master."],c:2,e:"The Developers forecast how much work they can do in a Sprint based on past performance. This is an estimate, not a guarantee; Scrum emphasizes empirical learning, so forecasts can be adjusted if needed."},
{q:"How does Scrum encourage self-management?",a:["By eliminating roles so team members can do any job.","By requiring team members to report to the Scrum Master.","By allowing the Scrum Team to decide internally how best to accomplish the work.","By allowing the Product Owner to choose which Developer works on which task."],c:2,e:"Scrum's self-managing teams collectively decide how to accomplish work (who does what and how) without outside direction. The Scrum Master supports this autonomy but does not control task assignment."},
{q:"Which Scrum artifact is considered the 'single source of work' for the Scrum Team?",a:["The Product Backlog","The Sprint Backlog","The Definition of Done","The Burndown Chart"],c:0,e:"The Product Backlog is the single source of work undertaken by the Scrum Team. All changes to the product must be reflected in it. The Sprint Backlog is scoped to a single Sprint."},
{q:"The Scrum Master observes that the Developers often go over time in Daily Scrum. What might they suggest?",a:["Increase the time-box for Daily Scrum.","Reinforce that Daily Scrum is strictly 15 minutes (maximum) and encourage focus.","Replace the Daily Scrum with a written status report.","Remove the Daily Scrum if it keeps running over."],c:1,e:"The Daily Scrum is time-boxed to 15 minutes. The Scrum Master should coach the team to keep it within time, focusing only on progress toward the Sprint Goal, rather than extending or removing it."},
{q:"What does it mean that the Sprint Review should never be considered a 'gate' to releasing value?",a:["Work doesn't have to be done incrementally; it can be released anytime.","Stakeholders must approve the release at the Sprint Review.","The Increment can be released as soon as it's done; the Sprint Review is about inspection, not authorization.","The team should skip the Sprint Review if they plan to release."],c:2,e:"An Increment may be delivered to users before Sprint end, and the Sprint Review is not a go/no-go gate. The team can release any time once the Increment meets the Definition of Done. The Review is for feedback."},
{q:"Which action is outside the scope of the Scrum Master's responsibilities?",a:["Coaching the Product Owner on Product Backlog techniques.","Helping the team remove impediments.","Assigning tasks to Developers during the Sprint.","Leading Scrum events when needed."],c:2,e:"The Scrum Master does not assign work or tasks to Developers; that would violate self-management. The Scrum Master serves by coaching, facilitating events, and removing impediments."},
{q:"Which of the following is a commitment associated with a Scrum artifact?",a:["Product Goal for the Product Backlog","Sprint Scope for the Sprint Backlog","Test Coverage for the Definition of Done","Release Plan for the Increment"],c:0,e:"In Scrum Guide 2020, each artifact has a commitment: the Product Goal for the Product Backlog, the Sprint Goal for the Sprint Backlog, and the Definition of Done for the Increment."},
{q:"A stakeholder suggests adding a mandatory code review step to every item in the Sprint Backlog. What is the Scrum Master's best response?",a:["Immediately mandate it for quality.","Discuss it with Developers in the Retrospective to see if it improves quality.","Ignore it because Scrum does not allow code reviews.","Cancel the Sprint because of the new requirement."],c:1,e:"Adding process improvements like code reviews is a decision for the Scrum Team. The Scrum Master should facilitate discussion (often in the Retrospective) rather than imposing it unilaterally, encouraging continuous improvement."},
{q:"Who is responsible for writing and prioritizing Product Backlog Items (PBIs)?",a:["Scrum Master","Product Owner","Developers","Stakeholders"],c:1,e:"The Product Owner is accountable for effective Product Backlog management, which includes creating PBIs, ordering them, and communicating them clearly. Developers may collaborate on details, but the PO has final accountability."},
{q:"Which role is responsible for ensuring that team values (commitment, openness, etc.) are practiced?",a:["Product Owner","Scrum Master","Developers","Stakeholders"],c:1,e:"The Scrum Master helps the Scrum Team embody Scrum's values and understand their importance. While all members are responsible for values, the Scrum Master coaches the team and organization to live them."},
{q:"If the Product Owner is unavailable for a meeting, who decides how to proceed with the Product Backlog?",a:["The Scrum Master","The Developers, based on the most recent priorities","The absent Product Owner's manager","The Scrum Guide mandates the Scrum Master must cancel the meeting"],c:1,e:"If the PO cannot attend, the Developers use the most recently clarified and ordered backlog as input and can proceed with planning or refinement. Priority decisions rest with the PO, who is consulted later."},
{q:"Which activity is the Product Owner accountable for?",a:["Removing team impediments.","Communicating the product vision and goals to stakeholders and the Scrum Team.","Determining how to do the work in the Sprint Backlog.","Ensuring code quality."],c:1,e:"The Product Owner is accountable for communicating the product vision, Product Goal, and backlog. Removing impediments is the Scrum Master's role, and technical quality is ensured by the Developers via the Definition of Done."},
{q:"Can the Developers estimate the effort of Product Backlog items during Sprint Planning?",a:["No, only the Scrum Master can estimate.","Yes, the Developers collaboratively estimate effort because they are doing the work.","No, they just estimate when they get to the task.","Yes, but only if the Product Owner approves."],c:1,e:"Developers are responsible for all work of the Sprint, including estimation. They are best suited to estimate because they know their skills and velocity. The PO may provide business context, but estimates are by the Developers."},
{q:"Which statement is true about the Scrum Master's relationship with the Scrum Team and organization?",a:["The Scrum Master can be a manager of the team.","The Scrum Master enforces Scrum and is seen as a bureaucratic enforcer.","The Scrum Master is a servant-leader who coaches the team and helps remove organizational impediments to Scrum.","The Scrum Master decides which technologies the team uses."],c:2,e:"The Scrum Master is a servant-leader, helping the Scrum Team adopt Scrum and work effectively, and helping stakeholders understand which interactions help or hinder the team. They do not manage the team or dictate technical decisions."},
{q:"How should the Scrum Master handle a situation where team members frequently skip Daily Scrum meetings?",a:["Replace them with a written email summary.","Cancel the Daily Scrum since it's not being used.","Coach the team on the importance of Daily Scrum for inspect-and-adapt and encourage attendance.","Punish those who skip."],c:2,e:"The Scrum Master should coach the team to understand the value of the Daily Scrum for self-managing progress toward the Sprint Goal, and help the team find improvements rather than eliminating the event."},
{q:"In Scrum, who is ultimately responsible for adding details (description, order, size) to Product Backlog items?",a:["The Scrum Master","The Product Owner, possibly with input from Developers","The Customer","The Project Manager"],c:1,e:"Product Backlog refinement is primarily the Product Owner's responsibility, though they may involve Developers for technical detail. Ultimately the PO ensures the backlog is transparent and understood."},
{q:"What should a Scrum Master do when there is a conflict within the Scrum Team?",a:["Immediately replace the Scrum Team members causing conflict.","Ignore it; conflicts resolve on their own.","Facilitate a resolution by encouraging open discussion, applying servant leadership.","Take sides to resolve it quickly."],c:2,e:"The Scrum Master should use facilitation and coaching techniques to help resolve team conflicts, encouraging openness, respectful discussion, and focus on shared goals. Ignoring or taking sides is counterproductive."},
{q:"Who is accountable for the release of the product into production?",a:["Developers","Product Owner","Scrum Master","Scrum does not define release responsibility explicitly; the team as a whole ensures the product is releasable by meeting the Definition of Done."],c:3,e:"Scrum does not prescribe a specific release role. The team collectively makes the Increment releasable by meeting the Definition of Done. The Product Owner decides when to release for market reasons."},
{q:"Which role may reject or accept work based on meeting the Definition of Done?",a:["Developers","Product Owner (with the Scrum Team)","Scrum Master","Stakeholders"],c:1,e:"The Scrum Team inspects the Increment during Sprint Review. The Product Owner decides acceptance based on whether all PBIs meet the Definition of Done, accepting items as done if they meet the DoD."},
{q:"Can the Scrum Master also be a Developer on the same Scrum Team?",a:["No, Scrum Guide forbids combining roles.","Yes, but it is not ideal. The Scrum Guide allows flexibility, though separating roles is recommended for focus.","Yes, and it's recommended to fill multiple roles.","Only if the team is smaller than five people."],c:1,e:"The Scrum Guide permits role combinations in certain contexts but warns it may reduce focus. A Scrum Master can also be a Developer if all Scrum responsibilities are fulfilled, though dedicated roles are generally better."},
{q:"What is one accountability of a Scrum Master in relation to the Product Owner?",a:["Writing user stories for the backlog.","Helping the Product Owner understand backlog management practices.","Ordering the Product Backlog on behalf of the Product Owner.","Making financial decisions for the product."],c:1,e:"The Scrum Master helps the Product Owner with effective backlog management and product management techniques. They coach and facilitate, not take over backlog duties. The PO remains accountable for ordering and content."},
{q:"Who should attend the Daily Scrum?",a:["All Scrum Team members equally lead it.","Only the Developers (the PO and SM may attend but rarely speak).","Anyone interested from the organization.","Only the Scrum Master and Product Owner."],c:1,e:"The Daily Scrum is an event for the Developers of the Scrum Team. The Product Owner and Scrum Master can attend as observers if it helps, but it is not a general status meeting for others."},
{q:"A Developer realizes after the Sprint has started that they overestimated their capacity. What should happen next?",a:["The Product Owner must work overtime to meet the Sprint Goal.","The Scrum Team collaborates to remove or adjust some Sprint Backlog items to still meet the Sprint Goal.","The Scrum Master cancels the Sprint.","Stakeholders must add more resources immediately."],c:1,e:"If capacity is less than expected, the Developers and Product Owner collaborate to renegotiate scope (remove or defer some PBIs) so the team can still achieve the Sprint Goal. The Sprint is not canceled just for lower capacity."},
{q:"Which statement about the Product Owner's accountability is FALSE?",a:["The Product Owner can delegate backlog work to Developers but is still accountable for the backlog.","The Product Owner may represent stakeholder needs in the backlog.","The Product Owner decides how to develop the product technically.","The Product Owner communicates product goals and backlog to stakeholders."],c:2,e:"The false statement is C. The Product Owner is not responsible for how the product is built technically; that is the Developers' domain. The PO is accountable for what to build and for communicating goals."},
{q:"Who is required to follow the Definition of Done?",a:["Product Owner only.","Scrum Master only.","The Developers for each Increment, and if multiple teams are involved, they share one DoD.","Only stakeholders."],c:2,e:"Developers must conform to the Definition of Done for each Increment. If multiple Scrum Teams work on one product, they must all use the same DoD."},
{q:"A new person joins as a Developer and asks who decides which Product Backlog items the team works on. How should you answer?",a:["The Scrum Master chooses the items to ensure balance.","The Product Owner chooses and assigns items to Developers.","The Developers forecast which PBIs they will complete in the Sprint, in collaboration with the Product Owner.","Stakeholders directly assign their requests."],c:2,e:"In Sprint Planning, the Developers select which PBIs they commit to, based on priority and capacity. The Product Owner provides priorities and clarifications, but no external person assigns tasks."},
{q:"Who decides how the Scrum Team is organized?",a:["The Scrum Master, because they know Scrum best.","The Product Owner, because they manage the product.","The Scrum Team itself (collectively, since it is self-managing).","The project's program manager."],c:2,e:"The Scrum Team is self-managing; they decide internally how to organize and distribute their work. No manager outside the team should direct these internal decisions."},
{q:"Is it allowed in Scrum for the Product Owner to be the Scrum Master for the same team?",a:["Yes, the Scrum Guide allows one person to hold multiple roles if necessary, but this is not recommended as it may cause conflict of interest.","No, it is strictly forbidden by the Scrum Guide.","Yes, and it's considered best practice to combine these roles.","Only if the team is very small (fewer than 3 people)."],c:0,e:"The Scrum Guide does not forbid holding multiple roles, but warns against it because performing both PO and SM roles can conflict. Ideally these roles are separate."},
{q:"Which role is accountable for ensuring the Scrum values are lived by the Scrum Team?",a:["Product Owner","Scrum Master","Developers","Stakeholders"],c:1,e:"The Scrum Master promotes and supports Scrum, including helping everyone embody Scrum's values. While the entire team should live the values, the SM has the accountability to coach the team on them."},
{q:"How is empirical process control reflected in Scrum's roles?",a:["Only the Product Owner should use empirical data.","Scrum roles promote transparency, inspection, and adaptation: the SM enforces transparency, Developers inspect/adapt the work, and the PO adapts the backlog.","There is no relation; empiricism is only a project management concept.","Scrum teams use empirical control only for bug tracking."],c:1,e:"Empiricism is integral to Scrum. The Scrum Master ensures transparency, Developers frequently inspect progress and adapt their plan, and the Product Owner inspects the Increment to adapt backlog priorities."},
{q:"What accountability do the Developers have regarding quality?",a:["To conform to the Definition of Done and ensure every Increment meets it.","To enforce quality with inspections on other teams.","None, quality is solely the stakeholders' responsibility.","Only to write code; testing is optional."],c:0,e:"Developers are required to conform to the Definition of Done, which is the Scrum Team's quality standard. They must build the Increment according to these quality measures."},
{q:"If a Product Owner wants to change the priority of backlog items during the Sprint, what happens to the Sprint Backlog?",a:["The Developers must ignore it; priorities are frozen once the Sprint starts.","The Scrum Master will reassign tasks to meet the new priorities.","The Product Owner may refine the backlog, but changes to the Sprint Backlog can only be made by Developers and with consideration of the Sprint Goal.","The Sprint is automatically canceled."],c:2,e:"The Product Owner can refine the Product Backlog anytime, but the Sprint Backlog is owned by the Developers. If a priority change affects the Sprint Goal, the Developers and PO negotiate scope while keeping the Goal intact."},
{q:"Which accountability is common to all three Scrum roles (PO, SM, Developers)?",a:["Maximizing product value.","Ensuring transparency and inspection are possible.","Leading all Scrum events.","Building the Increment."],c:1,e:"All Scrum Team members share responsibility for transparency and inspection of Scrum artifacts and processes. Maximizing value is only the PO's accountability, and building the Increment is the Developers'."},
{q:"Which of the following is a Developer accountability?",a:["Facilitating Scrum events","Creating and adhering to the Definition of Done for each Increment","Ordering the Product Backlog","Providing Scrum training to the organization"],c:1,e:"Developers are responsible for adhering to the Definition of Done for each Increment they produce. Facilitating events is a Scrum Master role, ordering the backlog is the Product Owner's."},
{q:"The Scrum Master observes that the Developers are having difficulty self-managing their work. What should the Scrum Master do?",a:["Assign tasks to each Developer to improve clarity.","Coach and mentor the Developers on self-management and help them improve their planning process.","Remove the Sprint Goal to simplify their work.","Replace the Scrum Team members with more experienced ones."],c:1,e:"The Scrum Master should coach the Developers on how to self-manage and facilitate discussion on planning and organizing work. They do not assign tasks, remove goals, or replace members."},
{q:"Which task is the Product Owner responsible for in a Sprint?",a:["Setting the Sprint Backlog tasks.","Clarifying Product Backlog items and acceptance criteria during Sprint Planning and refinement.","Removing team impediments.","Hosting the Daily Scrum."],c:1,e:"The Product Owner is responsible for clearly communicating Product Backlog items and acceptance criteria to the Developers. They do not manage day-to-day tasks or run the Daily Scrum."},
{q:"If there is disagreement about whether the Increment meets the Definition of Done, who has the final say?",a:["The Product Owner, because acceptance decisions belong to the PO.","The Developers, because they defined the DoD and did the work.","The Scrum Master, because they enforce Scrum rules.","The Stakeholders, because they define quality requirements."],c:0,e:"The Product Owner has the responsibility to accept or reject work as done, based on the Definition of Done agreed by the Developers. The PO inspects and accepts it or asks for more if it does not truly meet the DoD."},
{q:"Who is primarily responsible for clearing obstacles to the team's work?",a:["Product Owner, by reprioritizing the backlog.","Scrum Master, by removing impediments and shielding the team from distractions.","Developers, by ignoring impediments.","Stakeholders, by providing funds."],c:1,e:"The Scrum Master's role includes removing impediments and protecting the team from distractions or outside interference. Developers raise issues, and the SM works with the organization to clear them."},
{q:"Is it the Scrum Master's responsibility to guarantee the team follows Scrum perfectly?",a:["Yes, the SM ensures 100% compliance with Scrum.","No; the Scrum Guide states Scrum is only Scrum if the whole framework is used; the SM encourages adherence but the team implements Scrum.","Yes, and the SM must punish deviations.","No, Scrum is just a suggestion."],c:1,e:"Scrum only works if all roles, events, artifacts, and rules are followed. The Scrum Master encourages and facilitates this, but does not guarantee perfection; the whole Scrum Team must embody Scrum."},
{q:"Who in Scrum is responsible for using the Definition of Done during Sprint Review?",a:["Scrum Master, to enforce quality.","Product Owner and Developers, to inspect the Increment and determine which PBIs are Done.","Stakeholders, to demand changes.","Project Manager, to sign off."],c:1,e:"During the Sprint Review, the Scrum Team (Product Owner and Developers) use the Definition of Done to determine which Product Backlog items are complete. Stakeholders provide feedback but do not set the DoD."},
{q:"What is the Scrum Master's stance on DevOps and technical practices?",a:["Scrum Master must enforce DevOps practices in the team.","Scrum Master is a servant-leader who encourages technical excellence by supporting the team's improvements (e.g., DevOps, CI/CD) but does not dictate technical solutions.","Scrum Master has no interest in technical practices at all.","Scrum Master should prevent developers from adopting new technical practices."],c:1,e:"A Scrum Master fosters continuous improvement, including supporting practices like DevOps and automation to improve quality and throughput. They coach and facilitate; technical decisions remain with the Developers."},
{q:"Which of the following is not one of the three accountabilities in the Scrum Team?",a:["Product Owner","Scrum Master","Project Manager","Developers"],c:2,e:"Scrum has three defined accountabilities: Product Owner, Scrum Master, and Developers. There is no Project Manager role in Scrum; any traditional PM responsibility is absorbed into the existing roles."},
{q:"A team member new to Scrum asks what 'focus' means as a Scrum value. What is the best explanation?",a:["Focus means the team must focus only on coding tasks.","Focus means everyone should concentrate on the work of the Sprint and the Sprint Goal, not on other tasks or changes.","Focus means ignoring stakeholder needs.","Focus means the team should not consider technical quality."],c:1,e:"Focus (one of the five values) means the Scrum Team concentrates on the Sprint Goal and the current Sprint Backlog items, not getting sidetracked by unrelated work during a Sprint."},
{q:"Which Scrum role is responsible for maintaining the Sprint Backlog during the Sprint?",a:["Product Owner","Scrum Master","Developers","Stakeholders"],c:2,e:"Developers maintain and update the Sprint Backlog during the Sprint. They add tasks, update progress, and adjust the plan. The Product Owner is not involved in day-to-day Sprint Backlog maintenance."},
{q:"What is the primary accountability of the Scrum Master in relation to Scrum teams?",a:["Removing management layers.","Ensuring that Scrum is understood and enacted within the team and organization.","Writing user stories.","Assigning tasks to team members."],c:1,e:"The Scrum Master's primary accountability is to promote and support Scrum's adoption, ensuring Scrum theory, practices, and rules are understood and followed. They do not assign tasks or write user stories."},
{q:"During a Sprint, who is responsible for keeping stakeholders updated on progress and getting their feedback?",a:["Product Owner (during the Sprint Review and other interactions)","Developers (through Daily Scrum updates)","Scrum Master (by sending daily reports)","Project Sponsor"],c:0,e:"The Product Owner engages stakeholders to review progress (often during the Sprint Review) and incorporates their feedback into the backlog. The Scrum Master may facilitate but is not the primary communicator."},
{q:"Which role does the Scrum Guide explicitly state may be part of the same person?",a:["Product Owner and Scrum Master for the same team (not recommended, but possible).","Scrum Master and Stakeholder.","Product Owner and Customer Representative.","Scrum Master and Project Manager."],c:0,e:"The Scrum Guide does not prohibit role combinations; one person could be both PO and SM if needed, though it warns against it due to conflict of interest."},
{q:"Who has the final say on the order of items in the Product Backlog?",a:["The Scrum Team collectively.","The Product Owner.","The Scrum Master.","The majority vote among Developers."],c:1,e:"The Product Owner is accountable for ordering the Product Backlog to maximize value. While Developers and stakeholders can give input, only the PO has the final authority on backlog priorities."},
{q:"Which of these is not one of the Agile Manifesto's four values?",a:["Individuals and interactions over processes and tools","Working software over comprehensive documentation","Following a plan over responding to change","Customer collaboration over contract negotiation"],c:2,e:"The Agile Manifesto values responding to change over following a plan. Thus 'following a plan over responding to change' is the opposite of an Agile value."},
{q:"The Agile principle 'At regular intervals, the team reflects on how to become more effective, then tunes and adjusts its behavior' is best exemplified by which Scrum event?",a:["Sprint Planning","Daily Scrum","Sprint Review","Sprint Retrospective"],c:3,e:"This Agile principle describes the purpose of the Sprint Retrospective. The team inspects its process and defines improvements to implement in the next Sprint, embodying continuous improvement."},
{q:"How does Scrum treat change in requirements?",a:["Change is discouraged after Sprint Planning.","Change is welcomed and can be made at any time through backlog refinement.","Change must be approved by the Scrum Master.","Change is only allowed between releases, not within Sprints."],c:1,e:"Scrum and Agile welcome changing requirements, even late in development. Changes go through the Product Backlog (refinement); the Product Owner then adjusts future Sprints accordingly."},
{q:"According to the Agile Manifesto, which is more valued?",a:["Contract negotiation over customer collaboration.","Documentation over working product.","Individuals and interactions over processes and tools.","Following a plan over responding to change."],c:2,e:"The Agile Manifesto states: 'We value individuals and interactions over processes and tools.' While processes and tools have value, the emphasis is on people and their collaboration."},
{q:"A team adheres strictly to a six-month plan and treats Scrum events as optional. Which Agile principle are they violating?",a:["'Deliver working software frequently'","'Individuals and interactions over processes and tools'","'Responding to change over following a plan'","'Continuous attention to technical excellence'"],c:2,e:"By strictly following a plan and not adapting, they violate the Agile principle 'Responding to change over following a plan.' Agile encourages adaptation when needed, which Scrum events facilitate."},
{q:"In Agile and Scrum, what is the attitude toward failure?",a:["Failure should be hidden and avoided at all costs.","Failure is an opportunity to learn (inspect and adapt).","Failure means the team must be disbanded.","Failure has no place in Agile; it must be prevented by planning."],c:1,e:"Agile embraces learning from failure. Scrum's inspect-and-adapt cycle exposes problems early through transparency and treats them as learning opportunities. Concealing or punishing failure contradicts Agile values."},
{q:"What does it mean for Scrum to be lightweight?",a:["It has very few rules and artifacts, focusing only on essentials necessary for empiricism.","It has no rules whatsoever.","It minimizes documentation by replacing it with strict contract clauses.","It only works for small, simple projects."],c:0,e:"Scrum is a minimally sufficient framework. It focuses only on core roles, events, artifacts, and rules needed for empirical product development. It does not prescribe practices beyond that."},
{q:"Which of these best illustrates the Agile principle of delivering value?",a:["Completing a large batch of features at the end of the year.","Regularly producing small increments of working product to get early feedback.","Documenting everything in detail before any coding.","Having monthly status meetings with stakeholders."],c:1,e:"Delivering small, working increments early and frequently aligns with Agile's focus on working product and early stakeholder feedback, allowing learning and adaptation. Large year-end batches delay feedback."},
{q:"According to Scrum values, what should a team do when a colleague brings up a tough technical problem?",a:["Avoid it, because tackling tough problems is discouraged.","Show respect by ignoring it.","Have courage to address it and collaborate on a solution.","Wait for someone else to solve it."],c:2,e:"Scrum values include Courage and Respect. Team members are encouraged to have courage to address hard problems and to respect each other's expertise in collaborating on solutions."},
{q:"One of the Scrum pillars is Inspection. What best describes this pillar?",a:["Continuously checking for compliance in external audits.","Frequently evaluating Scrum artifacts and progress to detect undesirable variances.","Inspecting code syntax for errors.","Periodic performance reviews of team members."],c:1,e:"Inspection in Scrum means regularly examining artifacts and progress toward goals to find variances or issues. Scrum events provide formal opportunities for inspection."},
{q:"The Agile principle 'Build projects around motivated individuals... and trust them to get the job done' most directly empowers which Scrum concept?",a:["Time-boxed events.","Self-managing teams of Developers.","Heavy upfront planning.","Strict hierarchical management."],c:1,e:"This principle highlights trust and support, which maps to Scrum's self-managing, cross-functional teams. Leadership should empower the Developers rather than micromanage."},
{q:"'Simplicity — the art of maximizing the amount of work not done — is essential.' Which Scrum practice most closely reflects this?",a:["Increasing story points.","Keeping only the highest-value items in the Sprint Backlog, avoiding unnecessary work.","Documenting all possible future features.","Adding more team members to speed up."],c:1,e:"Maximizing work not done means focusing only on valuable work. In Scrum the Product Owner prioritizes the backlog so only the highest-value items are pulled into Sprints, keeping effort lean."},
{q:"The Agile principle 'At regular intervals, the team reflects on how to become more effective' is implemented in Scrum by:",a:["Sprint Goal setting.","Sprint Retrospective.","Daily Scrum.","Product Backlog Refinement."],c:1,e:"The principle directly describes the Sprint Retrospective. The Scrum Team inspects how it did in the last Sprint and identifies improvements for the next one."},
{q:"How does Scrum implement the Lean principle of 'build quality in'?",a:["By having a dedicated QA team outside of Scrum.","By emphasizing the Definition of Done and continuous attention to technical excellence.","By only testing at the end of a project.","By letting customers test the product."],c:1,e:"Scrum embeds build-quality-in through the Definition of Done and Agile/Lean emphasis on technical excellence (e.g., continuous integration, refactoring). Quality is not just after the fact or external."},
{q:"Which mindset is not aligned with Agile/Scrum principles?",a:["Viewing change as an opportunity for improvement.","Inspecting and adapting frequently.","Prioritizing individual heroics over team collaboration.","Focusing on delivering working product increments."],c:2,e:"Agile emphasizes collaboration and team success, not individual heroics. A 'heroic individual saves the day' mindset undermines Scrum's team-based approach and values like respect and focus."},
{q:"In Scrum, who is responsible for managing stakeholder expectations?",a:["Product Owner, by communicating progress and backlog changes.","Scrum Master, by controlling stakeholder involvement.","Developers, by releasing code secretly.","Stakeholders, by understanding Scrum rules."],c:0,e:"The Product Owner typically manages stakeholder expectations, as they know the business context and control the backlog, communicating progress via Reviews and negotiating changes. The SM may facilitate, but the PO leads."},
{q:"Which concept is a trap or misconception in Scrum?",a:["The team uses velocity strictly as a performance metric.","The team commits to a Sprint Goal.","The team works together to implement the backlog.","The Product Owner orders backlog for value."],c:0,e:"Using velocity as a performance metric or goal is a common trap. Velocity is a planning tool (forecast) based on past Sprints, not a target. Treating it as a quota can lead to gaming the system."},
{q:"Which of the following statements is true about canceling a Sprint?",a:["The Scrum Master can cancel a Sprint if the Developers ask.","The Scrum Master can't cancel a Sprint under any circumstances.","The Scrum Master can only cancel the Sprint if the Product Owner is absent.","The Scrum Master has no authority to cancel a Sprint; only the Product Owner can, if the Sprint Goal is obsolete."],c:3,e:"Only the Product Owner has the authority to cancel a Sprint, and only if the Sprint Goal is no longer relevant. The Scrum Master or Developers do not have this authority."},
{q:"Which statement about self-management is correct?",a:["The team members work individually without collaboration.","The Scrum Team internally decides how to accomplish the work, rather than being directed by outsiders.","The Scrum Master assigns roles and tasks.","Management assigns tasks based on performance metrics."],c:1,e:"Self-management means the Scrum Team chooses how to work and whom to involve to meet goals. The Scrum Master does not assign, and external management does not direct the daily work."},
{q:"Which practice is not part of the Scrum framework?",a:["Pulling Product Backlog items into a Sprint.","Working on tasks selected during Sprint Planning.","Using Kanban WIP limits.","Inspecting progress at the Sprint Review."],c:2,e:"While Kanban practices like WIP limits can be used by Scrum teams, they are not defined in the Scrum framework. Scrum does not prescribe WIP limits; that is a Kanban concept."},
{q:"Which of these is a Lean principle often used in Scrum teams?",a:["Maximizing batch sizes.","Eliminating waste (any work that doesn't add value).","Extending release cycles.","Delaying feedback."],c:1,e:"Lean thinking, embraced by Scrum, emphasizes eliminating waste and focusing on value. Waste includes unnecessary features, delays, or defects. Scrum's short iterations and feedback help expose and reduce waste."},
{q:"According to Lean principles, which of the following is an example of waste that Scrum aims to reduce?",a:["Building exactly what the customer needs.","Producing large amounts of unused inventory (e.g., untested, undeployed code).","Collaborating closely with stakeholders.","Investing in quality tools."],c:1,e:"Large amounts of unused work (inventory) is a form of waste. Scrum's incremental delivery and Definition of Done keep work minimal and shippable, reducing such waste."},
{q:"Which of these aligns with Lean thinking as applied in Scrum?",a:["Accepting any work without question to maximize output.","Prioritizing backlog items by value and minimizing non-essential tasks.","Focusing on individual heroics instead of team process.","Maintaining large inventories of partially done work."],c:1,e:"Lean emphasizes value and flow. In Scrum the Product Owner and team prioritize high-value items and keep the Sprint Backlog focused, minimizing non-essential tasks and reducing waste."},
{q:"How do Scrum teams address knowledge sharing and cross-functionality?",a:["By maintaining separate specialized teams.","By encouraging Developers to work together on tasks and share skills.","By hiring only generalists and no specialists.","By having the Product Owner do all testing."],c:1,e:"Scrum teams are cross-functional; Developers share skills and help each other. Practices like pair programming or swarming enable knowledge sharing. The team as a whole holds accountability for the work."},
{q:"Which statement about Servant Leadership is correct?",a:["The Scrum Master dictates the team's daily tasks.","The Product Owner manages the team's work directly.","Servant leadership means the leader's main goal is to serve the team's needs and help them succeed.","Servant leaders do not set any standards or remove impediments."],c:2,e:"Servant leadership (the Scrum Master's style) is about serving the team: coaching, facilitating, removing obstacles, and supporting self-management. The servant-leader actively enables the team rather than commanding tasks."},
{q:"Which practice is a form of continuously improving the team's process?",a:["Adding more features to the product backlog.","Conducting the Sprint Retrospective to reflect on the last Sprint and agree on improvements.","Skipping daily stand-ups to save time.","Fixing a long-term budget in advance and not revisiting it."],c:1,e:"The Sprint Retrospective is specifically for continuous improvement. The team inspects what happened and plans improvements. Skipping retrospectives or not revising plans would hinder improvement."},
{q:"Which metric would be most appropriate for a Scrum Team wanting to improve its process efficiency?",a:["Number of daily emails sent.","Velocity trends over sprints (ensuring it's stable).","Number of code commits per hour.","Average story points per Developer."],c:1,e:"Velocity trends help a team understand throughput and consistency; a stable or improving velocity indicates process stability. Metrics like commits or emails are not reliable indicators of team efficiency."},
{q:"What is Kaizen and how is it used in Scrum?",a:["A backlog artifact.","A continuous improvement concept where the team makes small, frequent improvements (e.g., via Retrospectives).","A type of estimation.","A role in the Scrum Team."],c:1,e:"Kaizen (change for better) aligns with the Scrum value of continuous improvement. Scrum teams apply Kaizen by routinely reflecting and making incremental improvements to their processes, often in Retrospectives."},
{q:"A Scrum Team starts every Sprint with a full team-building exercise instead of Sprint Planning. Which Scrum value is this violating?",a:["Scrum value of Focus (not focusing on work)","Agile principle of continuous delivery","It's not a violation; any good practice is welcome","Scrum value of Commitment (lack of commitment to the Sprint Goal)"],c:3,e:"Skipping essential events like Sprint Planning undermines the team's commitment to the Sprint Goal and to Scrum's framework. While team building is good, replacing core events violates the commitment to plan the Sprint properly."},
{q:"Which statement best reflects coaching technique in Scrum?",a:["Directly telling Developers how to solve problems.","Asking open-ended questions to help the team find their own solutions.","Leaving the team to struggle alone.","Only intervening when work is overdue."],c:1,e:"Good Scrum Masters coach by facilitating discovery, often using open-ended questions to encourage team problem-solving. They enable the team to learn and improve rather than telling them what to do."},
{q:"How should a Scrum Master respond if team dynamics inhibit transparency (e.g., members hide status)?",a:["Remove the Daily Scrum requirement to avoid conflict.","Encourage openness and trust by reinforcing Scrum values and coaching the team on the importance of transparency.","Report the team members to management.","Cancel all Scrum events and let the team work independently."],c:1,e:"The Scrum Master should foster a safe environment encouraging transparency, reinforcing values like Openness and coaching on why honesty in progress is vital for adaptation. Punitive or avoidance approaches harm trust."},
{q:"Which statement is not aligned with an Agile mindset?",a:["Welcome changing requirements, even late in development.","Promote collaboration between developers and business people.","Rely on extensive documentation to cover all cases before development.","Value working software as a primary measure of progress."],c:2,e:"Relying on extensive documentation over working solutions is contrary to Agile values. Agile favors minimal necessary documentation and prioritizes delivering working software."},
{q:"A team is debating using story points for estimation. What Agile/Scrum principle supports using relative estimation?",a:["Adaptation is unnecessary in planning.","Focus on individuals over their interactions.","Plans can be adapted as needed, and relative estimation (like story points) is a practical method.","Use of story points is forbidden by the Scrum Guide."],c:2,e:"Scrum allows any estimation technique that works; many teams use story points to compare item sizes. Nothing forbids it in Scrum. The key principle is to use approaches that enable planning and then adapt."},
{q:"Which is an example of a coaching conversation question a Scrum Master might ask to improve team collaboration?",a:["'Why are you not working faster?'","'What can we do differently next Sprint to help us reach our goal more easily?'","'My way is the best way to solve this problem.'","'Stop having daily scrums; they're a waste of time.'"],c:1,e:"A good coaching question prompts reflection and improvement and encourages the team to find solutions. The other options are directive or negative, which are not effective coaching."},
{q:"Which statement about stakeholder management is true?",a:["Stakeholders have no role in Scrum and should not be involved.","The Product Owner invites stakeholders to Sprint Reviews and incorporates their feedback into the Product Backlog.","The Scrum Master manages stakeholders' demands during the Sprint.","Stakeholders decide the Sprint Backlog."],c:1,e:"Stakeholders engage during the Sprint Review to inspect the Increment. The Product Owner involves them and updates the backlog based on their feedback, aligning with Scrum values of transparency and inspection."},
{q:"How does Scrum support continuous improvement?",a:["By holding a Retrospective at the end of each Sprint where the team identifies and plans improvements.","By refusing to change processes once they are set.","By avoiding any reflection in order to focus on work.","By only learning after product release."],c:0,e:"Scrum explicitly supports continuous improvement through the Sprint Retrospective, a regular inspect-and-adapt opportunity. The team reflects on how to become more effective and then modifies its practices."},
{q:"Which is an example of embracing technical excellence in Scrum?",a:["Delaying bug fixes to after the next release.","Pair programming and continuous integration to maintain quality.","Only writing code without any testing.","Skipping refactoring to save time."],c:1,e:"Technical excellence is a key Agile principle. Practices like pair programming, automated testing, and continuous integration help build quality in and maintain a sustainable pace."},
{q:"According to Scrum, who should participate in Product Backlog Refinement?",a:["Only the Product Owner.","Only the Scrum Master.","The Developers and Product Owner (optionally with Scrum Master support).","External consultants only."],c:2,e:"Product Backlog Refinement is collaborative: Developers and the Product Owner work together to clarify items. The Scrum Master may facilitate. It is not meant to be done alone by the PO or SM or by outsiders."},
{q:"A Scrum Team finds they have too much WIP in their current Sprint, causing context switching. What Lean/Kanban practice might they adopt?",a:["Increase their Sprint duration to handle more work.","Limit the number of PBIs they work on at one time (WIP limit) to improve flow.","Abandon Scrum and switch to Waterfall.","Cancel the Sprint."],c:1,e:"Limiting WIP is a Kanban/Lean practice that helps identify bottlenecks and improve flow. The team can agree to a WIP limit so they focus on finishing before pulling new work, reducing waste."},
{q:"What is an example of a Scrum anti-pattern?",a:["Developers selecting work based on business value and priority.","The Product Owner writing detailed requirements and letting Developers decide implementation.","Scrum Master assigning tasks and deadlines to Developers.","Scrum Team using the Definition of Done for each Increment."],c:2,e:"A Scrum Master assigning tasks is an anti-pattern; it violates self-management and servant leadership. The team should plan and assign tasks themselves. The other options describe good Scrum behaviors."},
{q:"Which of the following is not described as an official Scrum artifact or commitment?",a:["Product Goal","Product Vision","Definition of Done","Sprint Goal"],c:1,e:"The Product Vision is not an official Scrum artifact or commitment. The official artifacts with commitments are the Product Backlog (Product Goal), Sprint Backlog (Sprint Goal), and Increment (Definition of Done)."},
{q:"Who is accountable for creating and maintaining the Product Goal?",a:["The Scrum Master","The Product Owner (with input from the team)","The Developers","The Scrum Guide authorizes only the team to make goals spontaneously"],c:1,e:"The Product Goal is the long-term objective and the commitment of the Product Backlog. The Product Owner is accountable for defining and communicating it, often with feedback from stakeholders and the team."},
{q:"What are User Stories commonly used for, and how are they defined in Scrum?",a:["User Stories are the only way to write PBIs in Scrum.","User Stories are a widely-used format for capturing requirements from a user perspective; Scrum does not mandate their format.","Scrum forbids User Stories; tasks must be technical.","User Stories refer to completed increments in Scrum."],c:1,e:"Scrum does not prescribe how to write Product Backlog items; many teams use User Stories to capture requirements. They are a common, useful practice for clarity but are not mandated by Scrum."},
{q:"What is an Acceptance Criterion?",a:["A mandatory Scrum event.","A detailed condition or test that must be satisfied for a Product Backlog item to be considered Done.","A type of burn-down chart.","A synonym for Definition of Done."],c:1,e:"Acceptance Criteria are specific conditions defined for a Product Backlog item that must be met for it to be accepted as done. They are not formal Scrum artifacts but help ensure transparency on completion."},
{q:"Why is relative estimation (e.g., story points) used instead of absolute time estimates?",a:["Because Scrum prohibits time-based planning.","Because relative estimation accounts for complexity and team capacity; it focuses on size comparisons rather than precise hours.","Because it looks more impressive to management.","Because the Scrum Guide requires story points."],c:1,e:"Relative estimation gauges effort by comparing items to each other, factoring in complexity, risk, and uncertainty. It is often more stable than hours. The Scrum Guide does not require any specific method."},
{q:"A Product Backlog item in the Sprint Backlog is larger than anticipated and unlikely to finish by Sprint end. What should the Scrum Team do?",a:["Immediately replace it with an easier PBI.","If still valuable, refine it into smaller items and continue; adjust the Sprint Backlog.","Count it as done anyway.","Cancel the Sprint."],c:1,e:"If a PBI is too large to finish, the team can split it into smaller ones, including what fits in the remaining time or removing what cannot. This preserves transparency and keeps focus on the Sprint Goal."},
{q:"Which best describes capacity planning in Scrum?",a:["Predicting exactly how many story points will be completed.","Estimating the team's available work-hours for a Sprint (considering vacations, etc.) to guide Sprint planning.","Assigning overtime to meet deadlines.","Not needed, since velocity does it all."],c:1,e:"Capacity planning calculates the team's available capacity in the upcoming Sprint, accounting for vacations and meetings, to decide how many PBIs to take. It complements velocity with actual available person-hours."},
{q:"Which statement is true about Velocity?",a:["It is the speed of team members.","It measures the amount of work a team can complete in a Sprint and is used for forecasting, but it is not a target.","It should increase infinitely every Sprint.","It is the same across all teams."],c:1,e:"Velocity reflects how much work the team completes per Sprint and is used for forecasting. It is descriptive, not prescriptive, varies by team, and is not a performance metric to maximize endlessly."},
{q:"What does refinement (grooming) typically include?",a:["Breaking down PBIs into smaller items, adding details, re-estimating, and ordering them.","Removing the least important items.","Reviewing completed work only.","Only writing code."],c:0,e:"Product Backlog Refinement involves breaking larger PBIs into smaller ones, adding detail such as description or acceptance criteria, possibly re-estimating, and reordering the backlog to make items ready."},
{q:"The Scrum Guide says the Product Owner is one person, not a committee. Why?",a:["To ensure there is clear accountability and single decision-making for backlog value.","Because committees are banned.","Because one person has more knowledge than a group.","Scrum has no mechanism for committees to exist anyway."],c:0,e:"Having a single Product Owner provides clear accountability and quick decision-making about priorities and scope. A committee could cause delays and conflicts, undermining agility."},
{q:"What is not a benefit of a well-refined Product Backlog?",a:["Items are clearer and understood before Sprint Planning.","The team wastes less time during Sprint Planning clarifying items.","Backlog items have consistent quality and are ready.","It eliminates the need for a Sprint Retrospective."],c:3,e:"A well-refined backlog leads to clarity, improved planning, and readiness. However, it does not eliminate the need for retrospectives, which serve to improve team processes. The other options are true benefits."},
{q:"Which of the following is a sign of a poorly maintained Product Backlog?",a:["Many large, vague items not broken down.","Backlog items with clear descriptions and acceptance criteria.","Frequent prioritization by value.","High transparency of backlog status."],c:0,e:"Large, vague PBIs indicate refinement is needed. They are not transparent or ready for development. Refined items have clear details; poor maintenance often means the team is confused about what to build."},
{q:"How should technical debt be handled in Scrum?",a:["It should be ignored to focus on new features.","As an emergency outside the Sprint so as not to disrupt planned work.","By creating Product Backlog items to address it, prioritized by the Product Owner along with other work.","By the Scrum Master, outside of Scrum."],c:2,e:"Technical debt should be handled like any other work: create backlog items for it and let the Product Owner decide its priority against other items. This ensures transparency and planned improvement."},
{q:"Which method is most consistent with Scrum for determining how many backlog items a team can commit to?",a:["Detailed activity-based planning for every task before the Sprint.","Empirical estimation using past velocity and current capacity.","Simply choosing as many items as in the previous Sprint.","Asking management how many they want done."],c:1,e:"Scrum encourages empirical planning: using past velocity and actual capacity to forecast how much work the team can take on. Management should not dictate Sprint scope."},
{q:"What is the purpose of a Release Burn-up Chart?",a:["To track hours spent on tasks.","To visualize progress toward releasing a product (work done vs total work) and forecast release dates.","To replace the Product Backlog.","To detail the team's internal communications."],c:1,e:"A Release Burn-up Chart shows work completed over time against total scope, helping stakeholders see progress and forecast when work will be done. It provides transparency into release readiness."},
{q:"A Product Owner removed several items from the Product Backlog after a Sprint. What must happen?",a:["The Sprint is automatically cancelled.","Nothing special; the backlog can be updated freely as long as transparency is maintained.","The Scrum Master must approve the change.","The Developers must pick new items to replace them in the current Sprint."],c:1,e:"The Product Backlog is continuously refined. The PO may remove or reorder items between Sprints. There is no rule requiring Sprint cancellation unless the Sprint Goal is invalidated."},
{q:"Who creates the definition of high priority for backlog items?",a:["Product Owner, often with stakeholder input, as they define value.","Scrum Master, because they understand processes.","Developers, because they do the work.","Stakeholders, without any Scrum Team input."],c:0,e:"The Product Owner sets priorities based on value to stakeholders, product goals, and organizational needs. They may seek input, but ultimately the PO decides what is high priority to maximize value."},
{q:"Which activity is not a formal Scrum event, but is considered good practice?",a:["Sprint Review.","Sprint Retrospective.","Product Backlog Refinement.","Sprint Planning."],c:2,e:"Product Backlog Refinement is not a formal event in the Scrum Guide; it is an ongoing activity considered good practice. The other three are official Scrum events."},
{q:"If a Development Team realizes halfway through the Sprint that they cannot complete the Sprint Backlog, what should they do?",a:["Work overtime until all items are done.","Continue working and hope to finish.","Collaborate with the Product Owner to update the Sprint Backlog (removing or splitting items) to keep the Sprint Goal achievable.","Cancel the Sprint."],c:2,e:"The Developers and Product Owner should collaborate to replan the Sprint work, possibly reducing scope so that what remains still meets the Sprint Goal. Cancelling is a last resort if the Sprint Goal is invalidated."},
{q:"Which statement is true about release planning?",a:["Scrum requires a detailed release plan covering multiple Sprints in advance.","Scrum does not prohibit release planning, but it should be flexible and based on empirical data (e.g., velocity).","Release planning is the Scrum Master's main task.","Release planning is only done after the product is finished."],c:1,e:"The Scrum Guide does not forbid release planning; it is often needed for stakeholder planning. Such plans should be forecasts (not fixed commitments) based on empirical data, adapting as product and markets evolve."},
{q:"What is a user story in Scrum?",a:["A required template from the Scrum Guide.","A fictional example with no real use.","A concise description of a feature from an end-user perspective (commonly used, though not mandated by Scrum).","The meeting minutes of the Sprint Review."],c:2,e:"A user story is a lightweight format to express requirements. It is a common practice for defining PBIs, valued for communication, but Scrum does not mandate any specific format."},
{q:"What is the Definition of Ready (DoR) and is it part of the official Scrum Guide?",a:["A checklist that backlog items should meet before being taken into a Sprint; it is not part of the Scrum Guide, but many teams use it.","A formal Scrum artifact.","The same as Definition of Done.","A release milestone."],c:0,e:"Definition of Ready is a team-created checklist to ensure PBIs are well-understood before a Sprint. It is not an official Scrum artifact. The Scrum Guide defines Definition of Done, but not a Definition of Ready."},
{q:"Why might a Scrum Team use story points instead of hours when planning?",a:["Story points remove uncertainty by being precise.","Story points abstract away from exact hours, focusing on relative size/complexity which can be more consistent and encourage team discussion.","Story points are mandated by the Scrum Guide.","Story points allow the Scrum Master to set deadlines easier."],c:1,e:"Story points let teams estimate effort relative to other items, accounting for complexity and uncertainty, and encourage discussion without false precision. Scrum does not mandate story points."},
{q:"How is capacity planning different from velocity?",a:["Capacity planning is about team availability and time; velocity is a historical measure of output.","They are the same concept.","Velocity is the team's mood; capacity planning is math.","Capacity planning is the Scrum Master's role; velocity is the PO's role."],c:0,e:"Velocity measures how much work the team completed in past Sprints. Capacity planning estimates the team's available work-hours in an upcoming Sprint (accounting for vacations/holidays). Both inform planning but are distinct."},
{q:"What should a Scrum Team do if their velocity starts to drop significantly over several Sprints?",a:["Ignore it; velocity fluctuations don't matter.","Use the Sprint Retrospective to investigate causes (e.g., technical debt, impediments) and improve, rather than panic.","Fire the lowest-performing Developers.","Change the story point scale to increase velocity."],c:1,e:"A significant velocity drop signals something is amiss. The team should inspect for causes during a Retrospective and take actions to improve. Firing or manipulating metrics is contrary to Scrum values."},
{q:"What is lead time and why is it useful as a metric?",a:["Lead time is the time from idea to delivery; it helps teams understand how long work actually takes and spot bottlenecks.","Lead time is the daily stand-up duration.","Lead time is the sprint length.","Lead time is time spent on leave."],c:0,e:"Lead time measures how long it takes for a work item to go from request to delivery. Tracking it helps teams identify inefficiencies (long lead times may indicate bottlenecks) and improve flow."},
{q:"In Scrum, what is the best way to measure team performance?",a:["By comparing velocity numbers from different teams.","By their ability to meet their Sprint Goals and deliver value, rather than chasing numerical targets.","By counting lines of code written.","By the number of hours team members work per day."],c:1,e:"Scrum discourages using velocity or other metrics as performance measures. Effectiveness is better gauged by whether the team delivers valuable increments and meets Sprint Goals. Comparing teams by velocity is misleading."},
{q:"What role do burn-down charts serve in Scrum?",a:["Mandatory Scrum artifact for tracking progress.","Optional tools for transparency that show remaining work in a Sprint or Release, helping teams see if they're on track.","A replacement for the Product Backlog.","They measure team morale."],c:1,e:"Burn-down charts are common optional tools to visualize remaining work over time, providing transparency and insight into whether the team is likely to finish. They are not required by Scrum."},
{q:"A Product Owner has compiled a Vision statement for the product. How should this Vision be used in Scrum?",a:["It replaces the Product Goal entirely.","It guides the Product Backlog direction and can be used during backlog refinement, even though it's not an official Scrum artifact.","It determines the Definition of Done.","It is only for sales and not relevant to the Scrum Team."],c:1,e:"A Product Vision gives high-level direction. The PO uses it to guide backlog prioritization and communicate the product's long-term purpose. It is not a formal Scrum artifact but complements the Product Goal."},
{q:"What is a well-formed Product Backlog item?",a:["A piece of work that is vaguely described and very large.","An item with a clear description, acceptance criteria, and estimate, small enough to be done in a Sprint.","A task assigned to a specific team member in detail.","An idea saved in a spreadsheet."],c:1,e:"A well-formed (refined) PBI is small enough to complete in one Sprint, has enough detail for understanding, and has an estimate. Vague or huge items are not ready and should be refined before selection."},
{q:"How do Kanban WIP limits help a Scrum Team?",a:["They allow unlimited work in progress to maximize throughput.","They limit the number of items in progress to reveal bottlenecks and encourage finishing work before starting new tasks.","They automatically assign tasks to Developers.","They enforce work in only one Scrum event."],c:1,e:"WIP limits cap the number of items in a workflow state, highlighting bottlenecks and improving flow and quality. Scrum teams can use WIP limits on columns to focus on completing tasks."},
{q:"Which is a principle of Kanban that Scrum Teams can adopt?",a:["Using time-boxed events instead of continuous flow.","Visualizing workflow on a board and limiting WIP to improve efficiency.","Removing all processes.","Only working on one long Sprint."],c:1,e:"Kanban emphasizes visualizing the workflow and limiting work in progress to improve flow and expose issues. Scrum teams often use Kanban boards and WIP limits during a Sprint to manage tasks."},
{q:"What is cycle time in a Lean/Agile context?",a:["The Scrum Master's career length.","The time it takes to move a single PBI from start to completion.","The length of a Sprint.","Time between daily scrums."],c:1,e:"Cycle time measures how long it takes for one work item to go from start (entered active work) to finish. Tracking it helps teams improve flow. It differs from lead time, which includes waiting to start."},
{q:"In Agile project management, what is the relationship between scope, time, and cost?",a:["All three are fixed at the start and never change.","Scope is fixed; time and cost can vary.","Time and cost are often fixed in a Sprint, so scope is made variable (backlog adjusted) to adapt.","None; Agile does not consider these constraints."],c:2,e:"In Scrum, Sprint duration (time) and team resources (cost) are fixed, making scope variable. The team negotiates scope changes within the Sprint to meet the goal — contrasting with fixed-scope waterfall."},
{q:"What does flow mean in Agile/Lean contexts?",a:["How water moves in rivers.","The continuous, incremental progress of work with as little interruption or waste as possible.","The ordering of backlog by value.","The Scrum Master's communication plan."],c:1,e:"Flow refers to the smooth progression of work items through the system. Agile/Lean aim to remove interruptions or waste so items move continuously from start to done. Limiting WIP and removing bottlenecks improve flow."},
{q:"Which of the following is not a Lean principle?",a:["Deliver fast for customer feedback.","Minimize waste.","Empower the team to improve the process.","Maximize detailed documentation."],c:3,e:"Lean principles include eliminating waste, delivering fast to get feedback, and continuously improving the process. Maximizing documentation is contrary to Lean, as unnecessary documentation is considered waste."},
{q:"How does continuous integration/continuous delivery (CI/CD) relate to Agile/Scrum?",a:["CI/CD is required by the Scrum Guide.","CI/CD supports agile values by enabling quick feedback and frequent delivery of working software, aligning with Scrum's empirical process.","CI/CD is irrelevant in Scrum.","CI/CD only applies to hardware projects."],c:1,e:"CI/CD lets teams integrate changes frequently and deliver with confidence, supporting Agile values of fast feedback and frequent delivery. While not mandated by Scrum, CI/CD is complementary."},
{q:"What is cycle time a measure of, and why is it useful?",a:["The number of hours a person works per week; useful for payroll.","The time for an item to move from start to finish; it helps teams identify delays and improve flow.","The weekly meeting duration; it helps schedule events.","The time to deploy to production, which is irrelevant to Scrum."],c:1,e:"Cycle time indicates how quickly individual items are completed. Monitoring it helps teams see if work is flowing smoothly or if there are bottlenecks (e.g., a large increase in cycle time signals a problem)."},
{q:"How should a Scrum Team handle changes outside their control (e.g., a production incident for another product)?",a:["Continue as if nothing happened to keep the Sprint Goal.","Stop all work and focus on the incident until resolved, as Scrum events become irrelevant.","Assess the impact: Developers discuss with the Product Owner; the Scrum Master may help coordinate, potentially adjusting or canceling the Sprint if the incident changes the Sprint Goal's validity.","Wait until the Sprint ends to address it."],c:2,e:"If an external event significantly impacts the product, the Scrum Team must inspect and adapt — possibly taking the incident into the Sprint, and if the Sprint Goal is invalid, the PO might cancel the Sprint."},
{q:"A team uses Kanban. Which concept is NOT part of classic Kanban practice?",a:["Limiting Work In Progress (WIP)","Using pull signals to start work when capacity is free","Time-boxed Sprints with a fixed backlog","Visualizing workflow on a board"],c:2,e:"Kanban is flow-based (continuous), not inherently time-boxed. It does not use fixed-length Sprints or Sprint Backlogs. WIP limits, a pull system, and visualization are key Kanban practices; time-boxing is a Scrum concept."},
{q:"What is SAFe in relation to Scrum?",a:["The Scrum Master's nickname.","A lightweight extension of Scrum for beginners.","Scaled Agile Framework — a set of principles and practices for applying Agile/Lean at enterprise scale.","An acronym for Scrum roles."],c:2,e:"SAFe (Scaled Agile Framework) is an organizational framework providing guidance on roles and processes to scale Agile across multiple teams and programs. It incorporates Scrum principles but adds layers for alignment."},
{q:"Which of the following is one of the core values of SAFe?",a:["Transparency","Alignment","Flexibility","Micromanagement"],c:1,e:"SAFe's core values include Alignment, Built-in Quality, Transparency, and Program Execution. Alignment (shared understanding across teams) is key in SAFe. Micromanagement is not an Agile/SAFe value."},
{q:"SAFe emphasizes built-in quality. How can a Scrum Team contribute to this principle?",a:["By prioritizing features with no regard to defects.","By integrating quality practices (e.g., automated tests, peer reviews, refactoring) into each Increment.","By doing a final quality check only at release time.","By ignoring technical excellence."],c:1,e:"Built-in quality means quality practices are embedded in the workflow. A Scrum Team does this by adhering to the Definition of Done and using automated testing, refactoring, and continuous integration."},
{q:"One SAFe lean-agile principle is to 'deliver value incrementally in short cycles'. Which Scrum practice reflects this?",a:["Annual releases.","Iterative Sprints producing increments that can be delivered each Sprint.","Weekly status reports.","One long development phase with a big reveal."],c:1,e:"Scrum's iterative Sprints produce a working Increment every Sprint, aligning with the SAFe/Lean principle of building the system incrementally with fast learning cycles."},
{q:"According to SAFe, what is 'systems thinking', and how does it relate to Scrum?",a:["An Agile tool for coding.","Understanding the entire environment and context for the product; in Scrum, considering users, stakeholders, and organizational factors when making decisions.","A type of estimation.","A daily meeting technique."],c:1,e:"Systems thinking means understanding the product within its broader system (users, market, organization). In Scrum this aligns with including stakeholders in Reviews and recognizing that optimizing part may not optimize the whole."},
{q:"Which statement about Scrum@Scale or Nexus (scaling methods) is true?",a:["They are Scrum variations designed to scale Scrum to multiple teams by adding coordination roles/events while preserving Scrum fundamentals.","They replace the need for Product Owners.","They apply only to manufacturing, not software.","They discourage cross-team communication."],c:0,e:"Scrum@Scale and Nexus extend Scrum for multiple teams, introducing coordination events (like Scrum of Scrums) and integration teams while keeping the core Scrum elements and roles, and encouraging communication."},
{q:"In SAFe, what does it mean to 'take an economic view'?",a:["The team should make decisions that deliver the best value at the lowest cost, considering things like cost of delay.","Scrum teams should only consider technical details, not cost.","The Product Owner handles all budgets and ignores market needs.","Economics is irrelevant in Agile."],c:0,e:"Taking an economic view (SAFe Principle 1) means understanding the economics of development — costs, value, cost of delay — when making decisions. SAFe explicitly highlights economic reasoning at each decision point."},
{q:"A Scrum Team uses SAFe's concept of a 'Program Increment' (PI). How does that relate to Scrum Sprints?",a:["A PI is the same as a Sprint.","A PI is a longer cadence (e.g., several Sprints) that contains multiple Sprints; used in SAFe to plan and track larger increments of value.","A PI replaces the need for Sprint Reviews.","A PI means PBI."],c:1,e:"In SAFe, a Program Increment is typically a multi-Sprint planning horizon. It is a larger timebox containing many Sprints, used for program-level planning and synchronization, without replacing Sprint events."},
{q:"Which of the following is a high-level SAFe principle?",a:["Work in complete secrecy from management.","Apply unrealistic planning.","Assume variability and preserve options (instead of locking in a single plan too early).","Use a fixed waterfall plan."],c:2,e:"SAFe Principle 3 is 'Assume variability; preserve options,' advocating maintaining flexibility and not making irreversible decisions too early. This reflects Lean and Agile thought."},
{q:"What is decentralized decision-making, and how does it apply to Scrum or scaling?",a:["Only a single person decides everything (centralized).","Pushing decision authority to the person or team closest to the information; in Scrum, Developers and PO make local decisions without waiting for top management.","Letting customers decide all internal processes.","A principle that forbids Scrum Masters from making decisions."],c:1,e:"Decentralized decision-making means teams make most decisions locally. Scrum embodies this: Developers self-manage and decide how to do work, POs decide priorities without managerial approval — speeding up delivery and building ownership."},
{q:"In a scaled context, what is big room planning (like PI planning in SAFe)?",a:["A remote planning session.","A one-day meeting for team-building only.","A multi-team planning event where all Agile teams in a program coordinate work and objectives for an upcoming period.","A retrospective for executives."],c:2,e:"Big Room (PI) planning is an event where many teams come together, often face-to-face, to plan upcoming Sprints, align on objectives, and manage dependencies. It is about synchronization across teams."},
{q:"Which of the following is not an anti-pattern of scaling Agile?",a:["'Scrumfall': pretending to do Scrum but with long waterfall phases.","Aligning multiple teams on shared goals.","Ignoring coordination between teams working on the same product.","Overloading teams with irrelevant requirements."],c:1,e:"Aligning teams is a best practice, not an anti-pattern. Scrumfall, ignoring coordination, or overwhelming teams are poor scaling practices. The goal is to maintain Scrum's principles even when scaling."},
{q:"Which of these choices most aligns with the scaled agile mindset?",a:["'Our domain is completely unique; we cannot use common Agile principles.'","'We will use proven Agile and Lean principles (transparency, flow, systems thinking) as a foundation, and adapt them to our context.'","'We will do the same as before but use Agile buzzwords.'","'We do not need to improve processes; traditional methods are fine.'"],c:1,e:"A scaled agile mindset acknowledges complexity but relies on Agile/Lean principles to guide practices, adapting known principles to the unique context rather than ignoring Agile or using its terminology superficially."},
{q:"In large organizations, what is a common trap when scaling Scrum?",a:["Ensuring only one Product Owner.","Neglecting cross-team dependencies and backlog alignment (leading to silos).","Using Scrum events.","Empowering teams."],c:1,e:"A common scaling trap is not coordinating dependencies, with each team working in isolation on its own backlog. Scaled frameworks solve this with integrated backlogs and coordination roles."},
{q:"In SAFe, what is the concept of a 'value stream'?",a:["A fluid used in manufacturing.","The sequence of steps an organization uses to deliver a product or service, from idea to launch, maximizing flow of value to the customer.","Only about financial accounting.","A meeting in the Scrum calendar."],c:1,e:"A value stream is the end-to-end flow of delivering value from conception to delivery. It is the big process in which Scrum teams operate, ensuring alignment of work to customer value."},
{q:"What is velocity at the program or portfolio level in scaled Agile?",a:["It does not exist beyond one team.","The average velocity of one team multiplied by the number of teams.","A combined measure of throughput across multiple teams (often used for higher-level forecasting, but care is needed).","SAFe does not allow calculation of velocity."],c:2,e:"In scaled settings, velocity can be aggregated to forecast at the program level, though SAFe typically uses other metrics like Program Increment objectives. Conceptually it is combined throughput."},
{q:"Which of these is not a configuration of SAFe?",a:["Essential SAFe","Large Solution SAFe","Portfolio SAFe","Waterfall SAFe"],c:3,e:"SAFe configurations include Essential SAFe, Large Solution, Portfolio, and Full SAFe. 'Waterfall SAFe' is not a thing; SAFe is inherently Agile/Lean, not waterfall."},
{q:"What is a common challenge when implementing Scrum at scale in large organizations?",a:["Getting too much face-to-face communication.","Over-centralizing decisions and undermining team autonomy.","Teams releasing value too quickly.","Having too few roles."],c:1,e:"Over-centralized decision-making stifles the self-managing ethos and slows scaled Agile efforts. Scaled frameworks address this by recommending decentralized decision-making and clear alignment processes."},
{q:"How does Scrum ensure technical excellence in a scaled environment?",a:["By requiring code reviews in every Scrum event.","By mandating pair programming.","Through built-in quality practices (Definition of Done) and communities of practice across teams.","It doesn't; excellence is only in small teams."],c:2,e:"Scrum encourages built-in quality via the Definition of Done, and teams often establish communities of practice to share technical practices. Scaled frameworks maintain quality through shared standards across the enterprise."},
{q:"Which of the following is a common trap when learning Scrum?",a:["Thinking Scrum means no planning is needed.","Embracing inspect and adapt.","Collaborating in cross-functional teams.","Focusing on delivering value."],c:0,e:"A common misconception is that Agile/Scrum means no planning. In reality, Scrum encourages thorough planning (Sprint Planning, backlog planning) done iteratively. The other options are Scrum strengths, not traps."},
];
